725649f-b.title: Queens: 78th Street - 32nd Avenue
725649f-b.text:
78th Street, west side, 150 feet south of 32nd Avenue, showing the headquarters of the famous "Blaok Watch" during the Revolution. It was built more than 200 years ago and during the campaign on Long Island command'ng officers of the 42nd Highlanders, it was said, lived in this farmhouse. These views show the original location on Trains Meadow Road, an ancient 2igzagging country road, later obliterated. Views 1 and 2 are in a northerly direction; views 3 and 4, in a southerly. In the latter the house is in the center background. See the
"New York Herald.Tribune," March 8, 1936.
1923
Views 1,2,3,4
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

725648f-a.title: Queens: 78th Street - 32nd Avenue
725648f-a.text:
78th Street, west side, 150 feet south of 32nd Avenue, showing the headquarters of the famous "Black Watch" during the War for Independence. It was built more than two centuries ago and during the campaign on Long lIsland commanding officers of the 42nd Highlanders, it was said, lived here. These views show the original location on Trains Meadow Road, an ancient country road, later obliterated. Eugene L. Armbruster refers to the house as the W. Wright farmhouse and also as the Walker farmhouse. See the "New York Herald-Tribune," March 8, 1936.
1925
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
